==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Waylay
<hw>Way"lay`</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Waylaid</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Waylaying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[<ets>Way</ets> +
<ets>lay</ets>.]</ety> <def>To lie in wait for; to meet or encounter in
the way; especially, to watch for the passing of, with a view to seize,
rob, or slay; to beset in ambush.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Falstaff, Bardolph, Peto, and Gadshill shall rob those men that we
have already <qex>waylaid</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She often contrived to <qex>waylay</qex> him in his walks.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Waylayer</ent>⟦br⟧
